The Great Northern Forest

Four hundred square miles of unbroken canopy stretch between
Midgaard to the south and Kowloon to the north. This is no
mere wilderness -- it is a negotiated artery, governed jointly by
both cities under a compact older than most living institutions.

The Lantern Road winds through the forest along game trails and
dry streambeds, bending where the land demands. Its architect, Ilren
Voss, followed a doctrine called the Bent Mile Principle: the
wiser road is the one that bends around flood, den, and sacred grove.
Lantern posts mark each ford and turn in both Midgaard runes and
northern knot-signs.

The Northern Covenant, signed at a neutral glade called the
Oath-Crossing, forbids armies from marching the road in war formation,
restricts timbering to safety cuts, and declares shrine groves
inviolable. Neither city claims the forest as sole territory.

Two centuries ago, three successive Ash Winters -- volcanic fallout
from the distant Cinderteeth -- poisoned streams and killed a third
of the large game. Hunger turned territorial disputes into ambush wars
and forged the first Passage Tithe system, where caravans paid in
grain, salt, lamp oil, and iron nails rather than coin alone.

The forest is home to many peoples. Roadwardens and lamp-keepers
maintain waystones along the route. Mire-clans in fen basins trade
resin, fish oil, and medicinal bark from woven reed platforms.
Stone-antler circles guard megalith rings older than either city,
forbidding entry without ritual permission. Ashfang warbands --
exiles who blacken their teeth with ash -- raid road traffic and sell
intelligence to whichever city will pay.

Five ecological zones ring the road in ascending danger: the sunlit
Southern Verge, the treacherous Mosswater Bends, the dense
Ironpine Rise, the ancient Ancestor Deeps where luminescent
moss carpets the ground, and the cold Northern Crown where Kowloon's
Wardens of Iron conduct clearing patrols.

Recurring omens mark the forest's moods: the lantern-and-scale
motif carved on waystones, the split pine of adaptation on bridge
keystones, the white stag that appears before faction war, and
the red moss bloom that warns of corrupted groves.

