The Northern Corridor: A Ledger Perspective

Registry of Joint Governance, Northern Division
Filed under: Trade Corridor Administration, Lantern Road Operations

The Great Northern Forest is not wilderness to Midgaard. It is a
managed trade corridor -- four hundred square miles of negotiated
passage connecting our southern markets to Kowloon's delta ports.
Every lantern post, every waystone, every ford marker along the
Lantern Road exists because a clerk in the Joint Oversight Bureau
authorized its placement and a warden under the Oath of the Counted
Step confirmed its position.

The Northern Covenant remains one of Midgaard's finest diplomatic
achievements. Signed at the Oath-Crossing glade, it established joint
governance neither city could manage alone. Our Ledgerhouse holds
the original -- parchment eleven, northern drawer, third vault.
The Continuity faction considers it proof that process produces peace.
The Reckoning faction notes the fourteen sealed amendments no citizen
has been permitted to read.

The Ash Winters nearly broke us. Volcanic fallout from the
Cinderteeth poisoned streams and killed a third of the large game.
Patrol reports fill six volumes with logistics failures: spoiled
grain, collapsed bridges, convoy losses exceeding thirty percent. The
Passage Tithe -- payment in grain, salt, lamp oil, and iron nails
rather than coin -- was born from that crisis. Not generosity.
Administrative adaptation.

Our wardens maintain the Southern Verge with relay patrols and
quarterly audits. Beyond the Ironpine Rise, governance becomes
shared. Beyond the Ancestor Deeps, Kowloon's Wardens of Iron hold
primary jurisdiction. Handoff protocols fill three registry volumes.

Roadwardens answer to the Joint Bureau. Mire-clans hold barter
licenses renewed each equinox. Stone-antler circles receive ritual
access writs our clerks process but do not claim to understand.
Ashfang warbands appear in our ledgers only as losses -- raided
convoys and the unsettling suspicion that someone in our own bureaus
sells route schedules.

The lantern-and-scale motif on waystones is Midgaard's signature:
light and measure. When patrol reports note a white stag sighting,
the Bureau doubles escorts. When the red moss bloom appears,
quarantine advisories activate.

The forest proves governance can extend beyond walls. It also reminds
us that governance is never finished. Every season the canopy tests
another waystone. Every winter the road bends farther from where the
last survey placed it.
