The Great Northern Forest -- Trade Syndic Assessment

The Trade Syndics maintain a standing file on the Great Northern
Forest, updated each season by convoy marshals returning from the
Lantern Road. The assessment is blunt: four hundred square miles of
canopy we do not control, cannot bypass, and must use anyway.

Midgaard co-governs the road under the Northern Covenant, an
arrangement older than Kiess itself. The Syndics respect the Covenant
because it works -- caravans move, tithes are predictable, and neither
city garrisons the interior. But respect is not trust. Every marshal
who walks that road notes the same erosion: lamp-posts unlit for
seasons, waystones cracked and unrepaired, Ashfang warbands bolder
each year in the Ironpine Rise where Midgaard's patrols thin out.

The Passage Tithe system -- grain, salt, oil, nails instead of coin
alone -- is honest infrastructure. Our Syndics study it as a model
for risk-sharing along Roc Road. When the Ash Winters poisoned the
streams two centuries past, the tithe kept goods flowing where gold
alone would have failed. That is the kind of adaptive mechanism Kiess
was built to practice.

What concerns us is the Covenant's brittleness. It depends on
Midgaard maintaining its eastern commitment and Kowloon honoring
its northern patrols. If either city's attention drifts -- and
Midgaard's attention does drift, as Sepulchur Pasture and the
Eccentric Woodland demonstrate -- the Covenant becomes a sealed
document governing an ungoverned road. We have a word for sealed
documents that outlive their signatories: warrants.

The Roadwardens and lamp-keepers are reliable partners. The
Mire-clans trade fairly when approached without condescension.
The Stone-antler circles we leave alone -- their megalith groves
predate every authority on the continent and claiming jurisdiction
over them is the kind of overreach that killed Evermeet.

Wall Command maintains no permanent presence in the forest. That
is deliberate. Kiess extends its hand through commerce, not
garrison. Convoy marshals carry Syndic seals and emergency payment
authority for guide services. If the road stays open, we stay fed.
If the Covenant erodes, we will need new arrangements -- and we
will make them with whoever holds the ground, not whoever holds
the oldest parchment.

The Prism remembers: Evermeet ignored its supply lines until
they were cut. Kiess watches the forest because a trade city that
loses sight of its arteries is already dying.
