The Great Northern Forest -- As Kowloon Sees It

Harbor Syndics' Trade Assessment, Northern Corridor

The forest is not wilderness to us. It is the southern lifeline --
the only overland artery connecting Kowloon to Midgaard's markets and,
through them, to the continent's inland economy. Every bolt of silk,
every cask of salt fish, every barrel of phosphorescent dye that leaves
our Tide Gate by land must pass beneath those four hundred miles of
canopy. The Lantern Road is not a curiosity. It is survival.

The Courier Lantern Office maintains that the Bent Mile Principle --
Ilren Voss's doctrine of roads that yield to terrain -- is the oldest
expression of what we now call civic lantern-keeping. Our own signal
network descends from the same tradition: light placed where it is
needed, not where it looks impressive. Every lantern post on the Road
bears knot-signs our Lampkeepers can still read. That lineage is
not symbolic. It is operational.

The Northern Covenant -- the pact that forbids armies on the Road
and protects shrine groves -- was signed at the Oath-Crossing glade.
The Jade Magistracy notes with approval that its structure mirrors
our own Neon Covenant: an agreement inked in the open, resistant
to alteration in darkness. We trust compacts that glow under scrutiny.

The Ash Winters hit the forest two centuries ago, poisoning streams
and killing game. We remember this because the same volcanic fallout
from the Cinderteeth became our Ashfall Monsoon. The forest's
suffering and ours share a common source. The Passage Tithe system
that emerged -- payment in grain, salt, lamp oil, and iron nails --
is a language the Harbor Syndics understand instinctively. Coin fails
where material need speaks plainly.

Five zones ring the Road. The Southern Verge is Midgaard's porch.
The Mosswater Bends are treacherous crossings our caravans dread.
The Ironpine Rise swallows lantern light. The Ancestor Deeps
glow with luminescent moss -- the Courier Lantern Office calls this
the Forest's own Neon Covenant, light that cannot be forged. And the
Northern Crown is ours. Our Wardens of Iron conduct clearing
patrols there, keeping the road open within half a day's march of
the Jade Gate.

The Ashfang warbands trouble us. Exiles who blacken their teeth
with ash and sell intelligence to the highest bidder -- they mock
the Ashfall Vigil by wearing catastrophe as decoration. The
Wardens mark them crimson in the threat registry.

When the lanterns on the Road go dark, Kowloon's markets feel it
within the week. We do not romanticize the forest. We count on it.
