The Northern Covenant: What They Extend to Trees but Not to Us

From the Garden Ledger, Southern Archive
Annotated by the Bloom Pavilion Historical Committee

The Ember Wardens teach new recruits about the Northern Covenant
before they teach them about the three refusals. There is a reason
for this. You must understand what Midgaard is capable of before
you can understand what it chooses not to do.

Four hundred square miles of forest, jointly governed. Armies forbidden
in war formation. Shrine groves declared inviolable. Timbering restricted
to safety cuts. Two cities -- Midgaard and Kowloon -- agreeing
that a living corridor deserves shared stewardship rather than
unilateral extraction. The Lantern Road bends where the land demands
it. Ilren Voss called this the Bent Mile Principle: the wiser road
yields to flood, den, and sacred grove.

We read this in the Garden Ledger and we weep.

Not because it is wrong. Because it is exactly right. Because the
Northern Covenant proves that Midgaard understands cooperative governance
when it chooses to. Shared jurisdiction. Mutual stewardship. Passage
tithes paid in grain and salt rather than coin. These are our
principles -- the principles Elys Savan wrote into the Southward
Compact a generation before the Covenant was signed.

And yet. Three times Rakuen petitioned for inclusion in the civic
framework that the Covenant proves is possible. Three times Midgaard
refused. Incompatible accounting, they said. Route instability,
they said. Constitutional grounds, they said.

They will bend a road around a sacred grove but they will not bend
a charter around a living city.

The Ash Winters devastated the forest. Volcanic fallout from the
Cinderteeth poisoned streams and killed a third of the large game.
Midgaard responded with the Passage Tithe -- adaptive, humane, practical.
When the same ash poisoned our cisterns and killed our orchards,
Midgaard responded with silence. The Ember Wardens still maintain
the Cracked Promise Stone nearest the northern trail, where Savan's
apprentice carved: "They will share water with a waystone before
they share it with a neighbor."

The Roadwardens and lamp-keepers of the forest answer to a Joint
Bureau. The Mire-clans hold barter licenses. The Stone-antler
circles receive ritual access writs. Every faction in the forest has
a place in Midgaard's ledger -- a negotiated relationship, however
imperfect, that acknowledges their existence and their rights.

Rakuen has no place in that ledger. We are south of the wall,
south of the concern, south of the covenant that proves cooperation
is possible when Midgaard decides a thing is worth cooperating over.

The Garden Ledger Clerks keep a pressed lantern-flower from the
Southern Verge beside our copy of the Southward Compact. It is
a reminder: the light they hang for travelers, they will not
hang for us. But we tend our own lanterns. We always have.
